      <hedline>
        <hl1>Books Are Meant to Be Held</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>John Sanoudis letter says an e-book will never replace the real thing (July 6 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In 1963, I bought a book first published in 1955, ''The Eastern Schism,'' by Steven Runciman. I read this book several times and used it for reference since it has an extensive bibliography. Last year, I mailed the book to Sir Steven in England to ask him to autograph it. He returned it promptly with a nice letter.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In 1963, I bought a book first published in 1955, ''The Eastern Schism,'' by Steven Runciman. I read this book several times and used it for reference since it has an extensive bibliography. Last year, I mailed the book to Sir Steven in England to ask him to autograph it. He returned it promptly with a nice letter.</p>
        <p>How do you equate that experience with what you get with electronic books (''An E-Book Reader Priced for the Masses,'' News Watch, July 6)? Of what value is using a computer screen for reading when you ought to have the real thing.</p>
        <p>JOHN SANOUDIS  Aberdeen, N.J.</p>
      </block>
